            <p/>
        </context><steps><step id="step-1560420728918">
                <cmd>Download the module from the <xref href="https://forge.puppet.com/" type="http:" scope="external" format="html">Puppet Forge</xref>. </cmd>
            </step><step id="step-1560420744482"><cmd>To copy the module tar file to the modules directory in the controller container, run this command:</cmd><info><p><codeblock translate="no" xml:space="preserve">docker cp {moduletar} remediate_controller:/modules/{modulename}.tar.gz</codeblock><note type="important">The <codeph translate="no">modulename</codeph> must be
                            lowercase. For information on naming conventions, see <xref href="https://puppet.com/docs/puppet/6.4/modules_fundamentals.html#module-names" type="http:" scope="external" format="html">Modules
                            names</xref>.</note>This example is using the puppetlabs/reboot
                        module:</p><p><codeblock translate="no" xml:space="preserve">docker cp puppetlabs-reboot-2.1.2.tar.gz remediate_controller:/modules/reboot.tar.gz</codeblock></p></info></step><step id="step-1560420762589"><cmd>Create a directory to untar the file to, by running this command:</cmd><info><p><codeblock translate="no" xml:space="preserve">docker exec -it remediate_controller mkdir {modulename}</codeblock>For example: </p><p><codeblock translate="no" xml:space="preserve">docker exec -it remediate_controller mkdir modules/reboot</codeblock></p></info></step><step id="step-1560420780551"><cmd>To untar the module to the directory, run this command:</cmd><info><p><codeblock translate="no" xml:space="preserve">docker exec -it remediate_controller tar -xvf {modulename}.tar.gz -C {modulename} --strip-components=1</codeblock>For example:</p><p><codeblock translate="no" xml:space="preserve">docker exec -it remediate_controller tar -xvf modules/reboot.tar.gz -C modules/reboot --strip-components=1</codeblock></p></info></step><step id="step-1560420806940"><cmd>Restart <ph conkeyref="ProductNames/remediate"/> by running this command:</cmd><info><p><codeblock translate="no" xml:space="preserve">docker-compose run remediate restart</codeblock></p><p>On the  <wintitle>Settings</wintitle> page your uploaded module is listed as a task in the tasks table. </p></info></step></steps></taskbody></task>